I mean,
is there something I don't know?

792
00:40:26,465 --> 00:40:29,260
Hmm, maybe.

793
00:40:29,301 --> 00:40:31,262
Here.

794
00:40:31,303 --> 00:40:33,389
Open this.

795
00:40:42,022 --> 00:40:45,067
You're going to NYU.

796
00:40:45,109 --> 00:40:47,820
- [Elizabeth] He got in?
- [chuckles] He got in.

797
00:40:47,862 --> 00:40:50,281
Six hundred applicants

798
00:40:50,322 --> 00:40:52,450
for only five places. Wow.

799
00:40:52,491 --> 00:40:54,326
Like mother, like son.

800
00:40:54,368 --> 00:40:56,287
Huh? New York.

801
00:40:56,328 --> 00:40:58,164
New life, huh?

802
00:40:58,205 --> 00:41:01,250
[voice breaking]
Your mom would've been so proud.

803
00:41:02,334 --> 00:41:04,628
- [laughter]
- [soft jazz playing]

804
00:41:04,670 --> 00:41:06,630
Ah.

805
00:41:06,672 --> 00:41:10,384
To New York and Adam.

806
00:41:10,426 --> 00:41:12,428
Ah, to New York and Adam.

807
00:41:12,470 --> 00:41:15,264
- Hear, hear.
- [Elizabeth] To Adam.

808
00:41:15,306 --> 00:41:17,558
Yeah, um...

809
00:41:17,600 --> 00:41:18,976
I-I don't know.

810
00:41:19,018 --> 00:41:20,853
Don't know what?

811
00:41:21,854 --> 00:41:25,357
I'm just... not sure.

812
00:41:25,399 --> 00:41:28,319
About?

813
00:41:28,360 --> 00:41:29,862
[chuckles softly]

814
00:41:29,904 --> 00:41:32,198
Actually, I've been...

815
00:41:32,239 --> 00:41:34,283
thinking
about taking a gap year.

816
00:41:38,037 --> 00:41:40,498
Really?

817
00:41:42,041 --> 00:41:44,001
Wow. Okay.

818
00:41:44,043 --> 00:41:47,505
Um, s-so, you have a plan?

819
00:41:47,546 --> 00:41:50,716
You're gonna travel abroad
or...?

820
00:41:50,758 --> 00:41:54,303
I think that I should stay here.

821
00:41:55,304 --> 00:41:57,681
And-and do...

822
00:41:57,723 --> 00:41:59,517
do what?

823
00:41:59,558 --> 00:42:01,602
What do you mean?

824
00:42:03,896 --> 00:42:06,857
I think I should stay
in New Orleans.

825
00:42:06,899 --> 00:42:09,318
Like Mom used to say,

826
00:42:09,360 --> 00:42:12,029
go deep, not wide.

827
00:42:17,409 --> 00:42:20,204
Adam, want a ride home
in a real car?

828
00:42:20,246 --> 00:42:21,372
[all chuckle]

829
00:42:21,413 --> 00:42:22,831
[Adam] Yeah.

830
00:42:22,873 --> 00:42:26,210
- [Michael] Okay.
- They, they were here.

831
00:42:26,252 --> 00:42:28,337
Who?

832
00:42:28,379 --> 00:42:30,965
Jimmy Baxter
and his Celtic goon.

833
00:42:32,925 --> 00:42:34,093
When?

834
00:42:34,134 --> 00:42:37,054
As I arrived.

835
00:42:37,096 --> 00:42:39,598
Well...

836
00:42:39,640 --> 00:42:42,101
- It was a coincidence.
- Really?

837
00:42:42,142 --> 00:42:43,727
How do you know that?

838
00:42:43,769 --> 00:42:46,564
This is what happens, Elizabeth.

839
00:42:46,605 --> 00:42:48,232
Paranoia sets in.

840
00:42:48,274 --> 00:42:50,526
Irrational fear takes hold.

841
00:42:50,568 --> 00:42:53,070
We can't have that.

842
00:42:53,112 --> 00:42:54,905
That's the fight.

843
00:42:54,947 --> 00:42:58,450
We have to stay normal.
We have to stay strong.

844
00:42:58,492 --> 00:43:00,035
Okay?

845
00:43:00,077 --> 00:43:01,370
Yeah.

846
00:43:01,412 --> 00:43:03,497
Come on.

847
00:43:03,539 --> 00:43:04,832
Push...

848
00:43:04,873 --> 00:43:06,250
[Charlie] I love your father,

849
00:43:06,292 --> 00:43:08,085
and I love you.

850
00:43:08,127 --> 00:43:10,713
I'd do anything to protect you.

851
00:43:10,754 --> 00:43:13,090
So that's why I-I don't like it

852
00:43:13,132 --> 00:43:16,635
when I see something or someone
come between the two of you.

853
00:43:17,636 --> 00:43:19,597
Push it

854
00:43:19,638 --> 00:43:21,223
Pull it...

855
00:43:21,265 --> 00:43:24,268
Girlfriend leaning on you
to stay, Adam? Is that it?

856
00:43:24,310 --> 00:43:26,437
Girlfriend?

857
00:43:26,478 --> 00:43:30,691
I'm your godfather,
not your father.

858
00:43:30,733 --> 00:43:33,861
Well, godfathers get to talk
about girlfriends.

859
00:43:33,902 --> 00:43:36,280
You're gonna get left...

860
00:43:36,322 --> 00:43:38,782
- Okay. [chuckles softly]
- Come on.

861
00:43:38,824 --> 00:43:40,492
Now go for yourself

862
00:43:40,534 --> 00:43:42,286
It's easier taking candy
from a baby

863
00:43:42,328 --> 00:43:43,829
[chuckles]

864
00:43:43,871 --> 00:43:45,331
Don't hand me no bull

865
00:43:45,372 --> 00:43:47,291
Now you got it, baby

866
00:43:48,292 --> 00:43:50,336
[vehicle approaching]

867
00:44:06,644 --> 00:44:08,604
[Michael] Ms. Latimer?

868
00:44:08,646 --> 00:44:10,481
Frannie?

869
00:44:10,522 --> 00:44:12,650
- Hi.
- [Frannie] Oh, Judge Desiato.

870
00:44:12,691 --> 00:44:14,568
- Hi.
- Yeah, hi.

871
00:44:14,610 --> 00:44:17,655
I'm sorry to sneak up on you,
but I-I did want to catch you

872
00:44:17,696 --> 00:44:20,074
before school started.
It's about Adam.

873
00:44:20,115 --> 00:44:21,408
Oh, yeah? Is he okay?

874
00:44:21,450 --> 00:44:24,244
Yes. Yeah, he's... Well, he's...

875
00:44:24,286 --> 00:44:27,498
[sighs] He's waffling on NYU.

876
00:44:28,457 --> 00:44:29,958
Waffling?

877
00:44:30,000 --> 00:44:32,836
Yeah, he's saying
that he might not want to go.

878
00:44:32,878 --> 00:44:35,172
But he-he got the letter
and everything?

879
00:44:35,214 --> 00:44:37,716
Oh, yeah.
Yeah, and the T-shirt, too.

880
00:44:38,300 --> 00:44:42,179
Did he confide in you?
Did he say anything at all?

881
00:44:42,221 --> 00:44:44,181
No. No.

882
00:44:44,223 --> 00:44:46,725
Well, I know he trusts you,
doesn't he?

883
00:44:46,767 --> 00:44:48,727
And you're not his parent,

884
00:44:48,769 --> 00:44:50,354
so maybe you can get through
to him.

885
00:44:50,396 --> 00:44:53,232
I mean, it's like you said,
he's got something.

886
00:44:56,235 --> 00:44:58,487
I mean, he's only 17,
but he should know better.

887
00:44:58,529 --> 00:45:01,824
And I'm worried that he's gonna
throw it all away.

888
00:45:04,702 --> 00:45:07,538
I hate to ask, but...

889
00:45:07,579 --> 00:45:10,374
would you talk to him?

890
00:45:10,416 --> 00:45:12,543
Please?

891
00:45:13,544 --> 00:45:15,546
Slow, dramatic music

892
00:45:15,587 --> 00:45:17,005
- Sure.
- Yeah?

893
00:45:17,047 --> 00:45:18,507
- Yeah.
- I...

894
00:45:18,549 --> 00:45:19,967
Thank you.

895
00:45:20,008 --> 00:45:21,385
- Okay.
- Thank you.

896
00:45:21,427 --> 00:45:23,512
- I should, um...
- Yeah. Yeah.

897
00:45:23,554 --> 00:45:25,597
- Have a good day.
- Okay.

898
00:45:27,891 --> 00:45:30,310
Pulsing, dramatic music

899
00:45:50,456 --> 00:45:52,958
[Dr. Edward Grether]
Massive trauma

900
00:45:53,000 --> 00:45:55,461
causing multiple
brain contusions,

901
00:45:55,502 --> 00:45:59,590
the result of blood
entering the brain tissue.

902
00:45:59,631 --> 00:46:03,093
[Fiona] Can you tell the jury
what that looks like?

903
00:46:03,135 --> 00:46:04,928
[Grether] Okay.

904
00:46:04,970 --> 00:46:07,014
Um,

905
00:46:07,055 --> 00:46:08,557
the deceased was, um...

906
00:46:08,599 --> 00:46:10,142
You can call him Kofi.

907
00:46:10,184 --> 00:46:12,144
Ms. McKee, please.

908
00:46:12,186 --> 00:46:14,730
He's Kofi his whole life,
and then he gets killed

909
00:46:14,772 --> 00:46:16,315
and suddenly
he's "the deceased"?

910
00:46:20,235 --> 00:46:22,279
How did Kofi die?

911
00:46:22,321 --> 00:46:24,281
Kofi's skull couldn't expand,

912
00:46:24,323 --> 00:46:26,617
so his brain swelled up.

913
00:46:26,658 --> 00:46:30,788
The pressure inside his skull
reached an intolerable level.

914
00:46:30,829 --> 00:46:33,624
That pressure wasn't relieved.

915
00:46:33,665 --> 00:46:36,001
It's a terrible way to go.

916
00:46:38,253 --> 00:46:39,713
[Fiona] Exhibit B.

917
00:46:39,755 --> 00:46:40,714
[Fiona clears throat]

918
00:46:40,756 --> 00:46:42,132
[beep]

919
00:46:42,174 --> 00:46:44,134
Now, Counselor,
we don't need to go here.

920
00:46:44,176 --> 00:46:46,261
I just have
a few more photographs.

921
00:46:46,303 --> 00:46:47,971
[Michael] I think the jury

922
00:46:48,013 --> 00:46:49,324
has seen all
that they need to see.

923
00:46:49,348 --> 00:46:52,810
[Fiona] Uh... may I approach?

924
00:46:58,190 --> 00:46:59,775
Your Honor.

925
00:46:59,817 --> 00:47:01,860
Right. Please turn this off.

926
00:47:03,946 --> 00:47:06,323
I appreciate your concern
for the jury's feelings.

927
00:47:06,365 --> 00:47:08,784
You've seen the photos?

928
00:47:08,826 --> 00:47:12,788
Look, they're easy
for us to look at

929
00:47:12,830 --> 00:47:14,540
because we're used to them.

930
00:47:14,581 --> 00:47:17,793
But a jury? It's harrowing.

931
00:47:17,835 --> 00:47:20,587
And we don't know how sensitive
they might be to these.

932
00:47:20,629 --> 00:47:23,340
Do these injuries look
like they were caused

933
00:47:23,382 --> 00:47:26,426
by someone defending themself?

934
00:47:26,468 --> 00:47:28,345
I mean, even if the jury buys

935
00:47:28,387 --> 00:47:31,014
that Carlo wasn't the aggressor,
they still have to decide

936
00:47:31,056 --> 00:47:34,601
if the force he used to defend
himself was proportionate.

937
00:47:34,643 --> 00:47:37,145
These pictures go directly
to the heart of that question.

938
00:47:37,187 --> 00:47:38,540
They need to see them
to do their job.

939
00:47:38,564 --> 00:47:40,607
- Come on, Fiona. It's overkill.
- Shut up.

940
00:47:40,649 --> 00:47:44,027
And I need to protect my jury.

941
00:47:45,070 --> 00:47:47,114
Let's continue.

942
00:47:54,872 --> 00:47:56,999
[Fiona] Okay.

943
00:47:57,040 --> 00:48:01,587
We don't have any pictures of
what happened to Kofi's brain.

944
00:48:01,628 --> 00:48:04,548
So we're going to have
to use words.

945
00:48:05,173 --> 00:48:08,594
His head was bashed
repeatedly against the wall.

946
00:48:08,635 --> 00:48:10,470
[Fiona] How do you know?

947
00:48:10,512 --> 00:48:12,556
[Grether] Small particles
I picked out of the wound,

948
00:48:12,598 --> 00:48:15,517
some of which were embedded
in Kofi's skull...

949
00:48:15,559 --> 00:48:17,561
They match the wall material
in the cell.

950
00:48:17,603 --> 00:48:20,022
[Fiona] Stone from the wall

951
00:48:20,063 --> 00:48:21,440
was in his skull?

952
00:48:21,481 --> 00:48:23,150
[Grether] That's right.

953
00:48:23,191 --> 00:48:25,277
Well, a skull is hard, right?

954
00:48:25,319 --> 00:48:27,195
- [Grether] Very.
- So it would

955
00:48:27,237 --> 00:48:28,989
- have required...
- A tremendous amount

956
00:48:29,031 --> 00:48:30,782
of force to do
what was done here.

957
00:48:32,993 --> 00:48:35,412
How many bashings?

958
00:48:35,454 --> 00:48:36,914
Six.

959
00:48:40,083 --> 00:48:43,545
And what can you tell us
about the force that was used?

960
00:48:43,587 --> 00:48:47,591
Well, the, uh,
wall of the cell is flat.

961
00:48:47,633 --> 00:48:49,927
There are no significant bumps
or ridges.

962
00:48:49,968 --> 00:48:52,429
So, in order for particles
from the wall

963
00:48:52,471 --> 00:48:53,931
to be embedded in Kofi's skull,

964
00:48:53,972 --> 00:48:56,350
the force must
have been enough to...

965
00:48:56,391 --> 00:48:59,811
to loosen the material
of the cell wall.

966
00:49:00,938 --> 00:49:02,564
Which was?

967
00:49:02,606 --> 00:49:04,066
Concrete.

968
00:49:04,107 --> 00:49:06,068
He almost certainly had him
by the hair

969
00:49:06,109 --> 00:49:08,737
- when he was...
- So, wait. Like... like that?

970
00:49:10,697 --> 00:49:14,660
Like this? Like this?

971
00:49:15,661 --> 00:49:17,454
Yes.

972
00:49:21,750 --> 00:49:24,252
[banging continues]

973
00:49:24,294 --> 00:49:26,380
slow, suspenseful music

974
00:49:30,676 --> 00:49:32,886
[Grether]
I found Carlo Baxter's skin

975
00:49:32,928 --> 00:49:36,139
under his fingernails.

976
00:49:36,181 --> 00:49:38,266
[Fiona] What does that tell you?

977
00:49:39,518 --> 00:49:42,104
Kofi fought for his life
and lost.

978
00:49:42,145 --> 00:49:44,398
Thank you, Doctor.

979
00:49:48,193 --> 00:49:49,486
[Michael] Mr. Zander?

980
00:49:49,528 --> 00:49:51,655
[Zander]
No questions, Your Honor.

981
00:49:54,157 --> 00:49:56,159
Ladies and gentlemen, thank you,

982
00:49:56,201 --> 00:49:58,328
and we'll see you
in the morning.

983
00:50:20,684 --> 00:50:23,603
[clicking mouse]

984
00:50:32,404 --> 00:50:34,448
[phone buzzes]

985
00:51:19,117 --> 00:51:22,245
[sighs]

986
00:51:37,928 --> 00:51:41,932
No. No way.

987
00:51:41,973 --> 00:51:43,308
Who reported me?

988
00:51:43,350 --> 00:51:45,143
[Michael] That's confidential.

989
00:51:46,144 --> 00:51:48,563
I'm not allowed
to know who accused me?

990
00:51:48,605 --> 00:51:50,774
That's a habeas corpus suit
right there.

991
00:51:50,816 --> 00:51:52,275
Was it juror eight?

992
00:51:52,317 --> 00:51:54,152
I need to see your phone.

993
00:51:55,153 --> 00:51:56,863
This is ridiculous.

994
00:51:56,905 --> 00:51:58,698
Let's clear it up.

995
00:51:59,658 --> 00:52:01,326
Fine.

996
00:52:01,368 --> 00:52:03,161
Here you go.

997
00:52:26,476 --> 00:52:28,687
Oh, my God.

998
00:52:28,728 --> 00:52:32,357
That... that-that wasn't me.

999
00:52:33,900 --> 00:52:35,861
Somebody did this to me.

1000
00:52:35,902 --> 00:52:37,654
Why would they do that?

1001
00:52:37,696 --> 00:52:40,615
Ms. Long, I don't doubt
that you had good intentions,

1002
00:52:40,657 --> 00:52:43,660
but I gave
very clear instructions.

1003
00:52:43,702 --> 00:52:46,621
[stammers] You're not listening.

1004
00:52:46,663 --> 00:52:48,999
I didn't do this.

1005
00:52:49,040 --> 00:52:51,126
Someone did this to me.

1006
00:52:55,380 --> 00:52:57,716
What are you gonna do?

1007
00:52:57,757 --> 00:53:00,760
Replace you with an alternate.

1008
00:53:01,761 --> 00:53:04,598
This isn't right.

1009
00:53:04,639 --> 00:53:07,475
I could go out that door
right now

1010
00:53:07,517 --> 00:53:08,995
and tell the press
what happened here.

1011
00:53:09,019 --> 00:53:11,188
Sit down.

1012
00:53:15,567 --> 00:53:18,028
The trial would collapse
if you did that.

1013
00:53:18,069 --> 00:53:21,865
We'd have to start over
with a new jury.

1014
00:53:21,907 --> 00:53:23,825
Justin James would have
to come back

1015
00:53:23,867 --> 00:53:27,370
and relive the horror of being
curb-stomped all over again.

1016
00:53:29,080 --> 00:53:31,625
I think we both know
what's going on here.

1017
00:53:32,751 --> 00:53:35,754
I won't be intimidated
by anyone.

1018
00:53:40,550 --> 00:53:42,594
Do you have children?

1019
00:53:43,595 --> 00:53:45,388
A daughter.

1020
00:53:45,430 --> 00:53:47,807
And you love her more
than anything in the world?

1021
00:53:51,144 --> 00:53:53,188
What-what does she have
to do with...?

1022
00:53:53,230 --> 00:53:56,775
[Michael] Nothing is
more precious than her.

1023
00:53:56,816 --> 00:54:01,780
Not principle, not courage,
not conscience.

1024
00:54:04,115 --> 00:54:08,495
My guess is that you were
leaning toward

1025
00:54:08,536 --> 00:54:10,914
convicting the accused.

1026
00:54:10,956 --> 00:54:12,999
Hmm?

1027
00:54:14,292 --> 00:54:16,878
Let me tell you something.
I have sat through

1028
00:54:16,920 --> 00:54:20,006
hundreds and hundreds
of jury trials,

1029
00:54:20,048 --> 00:54:24,052
and I can always call them
by the end of day one.

1030
00:54:24,094 --> 00:54:26,263
I'm never wrong.

1031
00:54:27,597 --> 00:54:31,351
Justice won't miss you,
Ms. Long.

1032
00:54:31,393 --> 00:54:34,562
You can walk away,
and I would bet my life

1033
00:54:34,604 --> 00:54:37,357
that we will still get
the result you want.

1034
00:54:37,399 --> 00:54:40,485
Carlo Baxter is going down.

1035
00:54:40,527 --> 00:54:42,904
Plaintive music

1036
00:54:45,782 --> 00:54:49,452
Go home. Be with your daughter.

1037
00:54:49,494 --> 00:54:51,955
Pretend this never happened.

1038
